		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">tomaitheous wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"> On a side note, I've seen sites rounding numbers for scanline timings. Some listing 63.5us but 15734hz. 1/15734 is ~63.5566us.</div><br />As I understand it, the NTSC video system was slowed down 0.1% by so that the line rate would be exactly 1/286 times the 4.5 MHz audio carrier. So the line rate is the old system's line rate (15750 Hz) divided by 1.001 = 15734.265 Hz. This also happens to be exactly 227.5 color subcarrier cycles.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">How many master clocks is the NES and SNES outputting on a scanline? 1365?</div>
<br />1364. That's 341 dots, with four master clocks per dot, or only 227.33 color subcarrier cycles.

		

